.TH "sv" "8" 
.SH NAME
sv \- control and manage services monitored by \f[B]runsv\f[R](8)
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]sv\f[R] [\-v] [\-w \f[I]sec\f[R]] \f[I]command\f[R]
\f[I]services\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]/etc/init.d/\f[R]\f[I]service\f[R] [\-w \f[I]sec\f[R]]
\f[I]command\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \f[B]sv\f[R] program reports the current status and controls the
state of services monitored by the \f[B]runsv\f[R](8) supervisor.
.PP
\f[I]services\f[R] consists of one or more arguments, each argument
naming a directory \f[I]service\f[R] used by \f[B]runsv\f[R](8).
If \f[I]service\f[R] doesn\[aq]t start with a dot or slash and
doesn\[aq]t end with a slash, it is searched in the default services
directory \f[I]/service/\f[R], otherwise relative to the current
directory.
.PP
\f[I]command\f[R] is one of up, down, status, once, pause, cont, hup,
alarm, interrupt, 1, 2, term, kill, or exit, or start, stop, restart,
shutdown, force\-stop, force\-reload, force\-restart, force\-shutdown.
.PP
The \f[B]sv\f[R] program can be sym\-linked to \f[I]/etc/init.d/\f[R] to
provide an LSB init script interface.
The \f[I]service\f[R] to be controlled then is specified by the base
name of the \[lq]init script\[rq].
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
\f[B]status\f[R]
Report the current status of the service, and the appendant log service
if available, to standard output.
.TP
\f[B]up\f[R]
If the service is not running, start it.
If the service stops, restart it.
.TP
\f[B]down\f[R]
If the service is running, send it the TERM signal, and the CONT signal.
If ./run exits, start ./finish if it exists.
After it stops, do not restart service.
.TP
\f[B]once\f[R]
If the service is not running, start it.
Do not restart it if it stops.
.TP
\f[B]pause cont hup alarm interrupt quit 1 2 term kill\f[R]
If the service is running, send it the STOP, CONT, HUP, ALRM, INT, QUIT,
USR1, USR2, TERM, or KILL signal respectively.
.TP
\f[B]exit\f[R]
If the service is running, send it the TERM signal, and the CONT signal.
Do not restart the service.
If the service is down, and no log service exists, \f[B]runsv\f[R](8)
exits.
If the service is down and a log service exists, \f[B]runsv\f[R](8)
closes the standard input of the log service and waits for it to
terminate.
If the log service is down, \f[B]runsv\f[R](8) exits.
This command is ignored if it is given to an appendant log service.
.PP
\f[B]sv\f[R] actually looks only at the first character of these
\f[I]command\f[R]s.
.SS Commands compatible to LSB init script actions
.TP
\f[B]status\f[R]
Same as \f[I]status\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]start\f[R]
Same as \f[I]up\f[R], but wait up to 7 seconds for the command to take
effect.
Then report the status or timeout.
If the script \f[I]./check\f[R] exists in the service directory,
\f[B]sv\f[R] runs this script to check whether the service is up and
available; it\[aq]s considered to be available if \f[I]./check\f[R]
exits with 0.
.TP
\f[B]stop\f[R]
Same as \f[I]down\f[R], but wait up to 7 seconds for the service to
become down.
Then report the status or timeout.
.TP
\f[B]reload\f[R]
Same as \f[I]hup\f[R], and additionally report the status afterwards.
.TP
\f[B]restart\f[R]
Send the commands \f[I]term\f[R], \f[I]cont\f[R], and \f[I]up\f[R] to
the service, and wait up to 7 seconds for the service to restart.
Then report the status or timeout.
If the script \f[I]./check\f[R] exists in the service directory,
\f[B]sv\f[R] runs this script to check whether the service is up and
available again; it\[aq]s considered to be available if
\f[I]./check\f[R] exits with 0.
.TP
\f[B]shutdown\f[R]
Same as \f[I]exit\f[R], but wait up to 7 seconds for the
\f[B]runsv\f[R](8) process to terminate.
Then report the status or timeout.
.TP
\f[B]force\-stop\f[R]
Same as \f[I]down\f[R], but wait up to 7 seconds for the service to
become down.
Then report the status, and on timeout send the service the
\f[I]kill\f[R] command.
.TP
\f[B]force\-reload\f[R]
Send the service the \f[I]term\f[R] and \f[I]cont\f[R] commands, and
wait up to 7 seconds for the service to restart.
Then report the status, and on timeout send the service the
\f[I]kill\f[R] command.
.TP
\f[B]force\-restart\f[R]
Send the service the \f[I]term\f[R], \f[I]cont\f[R] and \f[I]up\f[R]
commands, and wait up to 7 seconds for the service to restart.
Then report the status, and on timeout send the service the
\f[I]kill\f[R] command.
If the script \f[I]./check\f[R] exists in the service directory,
\f[B]sv\f[R] runs this script to check whether the service is up and
available again; it\[aq]s considered to be available if
\f[I]./check\f[R] exits with 0.
.TP
\f[B]force\-shutdown\f[R]
Same as \f[I]exit\f[R], but wait up to 7 seconds for the
\f[B]runsv\f[R](8) process to terminate.
Then report the status, and on timeout send the service the
\f[I]kill\f[R] command.
.TP
\f[B]try\-restart\f[R]
if the service is running, send it the \f[I]term\f[R] and \f[I]cont\f[R]
commands, and wait up to 7 seconds for the service to restart.
Then report the status or timeout.
.SS Additional Commands
.TP
\f[B]check\f[R]
Check for the service to be in the state that\[aq]s been requested (up
or down).
Wait up to 7 seconds for the service to reach the requested state, then
report the status or timeout.
If the requested state of the service is \f[I]up\f[R], and the script
\f[I]./check\f[R] exists in the service directory, \f[B]sv\f[R] runs
this script to check whether the service is up and running; it\[aq]s
considered to be up if \f[I]./check\f[R] exits with 0.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-v\f[R]
If the \f[I]command\f[R] is up, down, term, once, cont, or exit, then
wait up to 7 seconds for the command to take effect.
Then report the status or timeout.
.TP
\f[B]\-w\f[R] \f[I]sec\f[R]
Override the default timeout of 7 seconds with \f[I]sec\f[R] seconds.
This option implies \f[I]\-v\f[R].
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
\f[B]SVDIR\f[R]
The environment variable $SVDIR overrides the default services directory
\f[I]/service/\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]SVWAIT\f[R]
The environment variable $SVWAIT overrides the default 7 seconds to wait
for a command to take effect.
It is overridden by the \-w option.
.SH EXIT CODES
\f[B]sv\f[R] exits 0, if the \f[I]command\f[R] was successfully sent to
all \f[I]services\f[R], and, if it was told to wait, the
\f[I]command\f[R] has taken effect to all services.
.PP
For each \f[I]service\f[R] that caused an error (e.g.\ the directory is
not controlled by a \f[B]runsv\f[R](8) process, or \f[B]sv\f[R] timed
out while waiting), \f[B]sv\f[R] increases the exit code by one and
exits non zero.
The maximum is 99.
\f[B]sv\f[R] exits 100 on error.
.PP
If \f[B]sv\f[R] is called with a base name other than \f[B]sv\f[R]: it
exits 1 on timeout or trouble sending the command; if the
\f[I]command\f[R] is \f[B]status\f[R], it exits 3 if the service is
down, and 4 if the status is unknown; it exits 2 on wrong usage, and 151
on error.
